```java
import org.junit.runners.Suite;

@RunWith(Suite.class)
@Suite.SuiteClasses({
   FirstTest.class,
   SecondTest.class
})

public class Main {
    // No need to define a main method for SuiteRunner
}
```

In the above code, you are importing necessary classes and setting up the test suite using `@SuiteClasses` annotation. `@SuiteClasses` is used to define the test classes to be included in the test suite.

Note: Replace `FirstTest.class` and `SecondTest.class` with the actual classes you want to test.

You also need to have JUnit library added to your project. If you are using Maven add the following dependency in your pom.xml:

```xml
<dependency>
   <groupId>junit</groupId>
   <artifactId>junit</artifactId>
   <version>4.12</version>
   <scope>test</scope>
</dependency>
```

If you are using Gradle, you can add this dependency in your build.gradle:

```groovy
testImplementation 'junit:junit:4.12'
```

For a full example to include other libraries in your project, you would have to add those libraries in a similar way. For example, to include log4j you would add the following to your pom.xml:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.apache.logging.log4j</groupId>
    <artifactId>log4j-api</artifactId>
    <version>2.17.1</version>
</dependency>
```

Or your gradle:

```groovy
implementation 'org.apache.logging.log4j:log4j-api:2.17.1'
```

Remember, libraries should only be included if you need the classes and methods provided by the libraries to perform your tests. If the library isn't needed for your code's execution, adding it as a dependency will cause an increased build size, as the entire library is included in the build. This adds unnecessary bloat and can decrease performance.
